{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658860"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20831"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20831"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13706"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79657"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11660"},{"type":"tags","id":"11661"},{"type":"tags","id":"12657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECongenital anomalies can be classified based on their underlying pathogenesis and timing during embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a disruption as a type of congenital anomaly?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abnormal tissue differentiation during organogenesis","Extrinsic interference with previously normal development","Failure of normal developmental field closure","Intrinsic genetic error affecting multiple structures","Abnormal regression of embryonic structures"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA disruption is defined as a morphologic defect resulting from \u003Cstrong\u003Eextrinsic interference with previously normal development\u003C/strong\u003E. This contrasts with malformations, which result from intrinsic errors in development. Disruptions typically produce random, asymmetric defects that do not follow embryological patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmniotic band syndrome is a classic example of a disruption. It occurs when the amnion ruptures, creating fibrous strands that can entangle developing foetal structures, causing constriction rings, amputations, and asymmetric defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal tissue differentiation during organogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E describes a malformation, which results from an intrinsic developmental error during the formation of organs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailure of normal developmental field closure\u003C/strong\u003E describes a specific type of malformation such as neural tube defects, not a disruption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntrinsic genetic error affecting multiple structures\u003C/strong\u003E would typically cause a malformation syndrome with predictable patterns of defects\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal regression of embryonic structures\u003C/strong\u003E describes a specific developmental error rather than an extrinsic disruption of normal development\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther examples of disruptions include vascular disruptions (causing limb defects or intestinal atresia) and teratogen exposures that interfere with previously normal structures rather than causing primary malformations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Disruptions are congenital anomalies caused by extrinsic factors that interfere with previously normal development.","Amniotic band syndrome is a classic example of a disruption that causes random, asymmetric defects including limb constrictions and amputations.","Disruptions differ from malformations, which result from intrinsic developmental errors during organogenesis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 10; page 454."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79657"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20831"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79657"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:42:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:44:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13706"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97041"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11660"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Concepts in congenital abnormalities","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":9,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11661"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Congenital anomalies","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:39+10:30"},"